<subSubSection id="6EF16510FF8AFFA7F78522C4FB0EFC8E" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" type="key">
<keyStep id="9D1F2E3EFF8AFFA7F78522C4FB0EFEA7" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F78522C4FB0EFE88" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F78522C4FB0EFE88" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
1. Posterior notopleural seta white (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F50C22C4FD99FF6D" box="[559,606,230,252]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1780,1802]" captionTargetBox="[355,1053,1025,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-288@1.[331,1075,1015,1767]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–3. C. absinthi. 1 — ♀, habitus, right; 2 — mesonotum, dorsally; 3 — wing (SIZK)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452426/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F54A22C4FD45FF6D" box="[617,642,230,252]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,937,959]" captionTargetBox="[331,1069,174,931]" captionTargetId="figure-314@4.[316,1089,171,940]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 17–20. C. loewiana. 17 — ♀, habitus, right; 18 — mesonotum, dorsally; 19 — wing (SIZK); 20 — abdomen (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452432" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452432/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">17</figureCitation>
); frons with fine setulae above lunule. Glans with compound, strongly curved rostrum. ................................................................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F7852302FB0EFEA7" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" box="[166,1225,288,310]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F7852302FB0EFEA7" box="[166,1225,288,310]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">— Both notopleural setae unicolor, black; frons bare. Glans with simple, tubular or flat, rostrum. ........... 3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="9D1F2E3EFF8AFFA7F785231FFB0EFE39" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F785231FFB0EFEFE" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F785231FFB0EFEFE" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
2. Femora completely yellow (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F6DD231FFDE8FEC2" box="[510,559,317,339]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1780,1802]" captionTargetBox="[355,1053,1025,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-288@1.[331,1075,1015,1767]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–3. C. absinthi. 1 — ♀, habitus, right; 2 — mesonotum, dorsally; 3 — wing (SIZK)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452426/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 1</figureCitation>
); apex of cell r2+3 with one large spot, base of r4+5 with wide, subquadrate hyaline spot (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F6EE237BFE38FEFE" box="[461,511,345,367]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1780,1802]" captionTargetBox="[355,1053,1025,1745]" captionTargetId="figure-288@1.[331,1075,1015,1767]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–3. C. absinthi. 1 — ♀, habitus, right; 2 — mesonotum, dorsally; 3 — wing (SIZK)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452426/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 3</figureCitation>
). ......................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="E1EB4D18FF8AFFA7F3782378FB0EFEFE" box="[1115,1225,346,367]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="absinthii">
<emphasis id="149FEA89FF8AFFA7F3782378FB0EFEFE" box="[1115,1225,346,367]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">C. absinthii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F7852354FB0EFE39" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F7852354FB0EFE39" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
— Femora at least in basal part black (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F5632354FDBAFE1D" box="[576,637,374,396]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,937,959]" captionTargetBox="[331,1069,174,931]" captionTargetId="figure-314@4.[316,1089,171,940]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 17–20. C. loewiana. 17 — ♀, habitus, right; 18 — mesonotum, dorsally; 19 — wing (SIZK); 20 — abdomen (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452432" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452432/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 17</figureCitation>
); apex of cell r2+3 with two isolated spots, base r4+5 with one oval spot (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F67723B1FE56FE38" box="[340,401,403,425]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[166,199,937,959]" captionTargetBox="[331,1069,174,931]" captionTargetId="figure-314@4.[316,1089,171,940]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 17–20. C. loewiana. 17 — ♀, habitus, right; 18 — mesonotum, dorsally; 19 — wing (SIZK); 20 — abdomen (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452432" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452432/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 19</figureCitation>
) ............................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName id="E1EB4D18FF8AFFA7F37B23B6FB0EFE39" baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[1112,1225,403,425]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Campiglossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loewiana">
<emphasis id="149FEA89FF8AFFA7F37B23B6FB0EFE39" box="[1112,1225,403,425]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">C. loewiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="9D1F2E3EFF8AFFA7F7852392FB0EFE72" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F7852392FB0EFE57" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" box="[166,1225,432,454]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F7852392FB0EFE57" box="[166,1225,432,454]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
3. Cell br with 3 hyaline rounded spots; stigma with one hyaline spot (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F45A2392FC6BFE57" box="[889,940,432,454]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1157,1179]" captionTargetBox="[369,1027,170,1103]" captionTargetId="figure-177@2.[359,1040,164,1126]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 4–11. C. difficilis. 4 — ♀, habitus, left; 5 — mesonotum, dorsally; 6 — wing (SIZK); 7 — abdomen; 8 — epandrium; 9 — glans; 10 — aculeus, ventrally; 11 — same, apex, enlarged (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452428/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 6</figureCitation>
). ............................................. 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F78523EFFB0EFE72" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" box="[166,1225,461,483]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F78523EFFB0EFE72" box="[166,1225,461,483]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">— Cell br with 2 hyaline rounded spots; other characters variable. ................................................................. 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="9D1F2E3EFF8AFFA7F78523CBFB0EFDA8" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F78523CBFB0EFD8A" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F78523CBFB0EFD8A" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
4. Wing pattern dark brown (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F6CE23CBFDDAFE6E" box="[493,541,489,511]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1157,1179]" captionTargetBox="[369,1027,170,1103]" captionTargetId="figure-177@2.[359,1040,164,1126]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 4–11. C. difficilis. 4 — ♀, habitus, left; 5 — mesonotum, dorsally; 6 — wing (SIZK); 7 — abdomen; 8 — epandrium; 9 — glans; 10 — aculeus, ventrally; 11 — same, apex, enlarged (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452428/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 6</figureCitation>
); mesonotum with three brownish longitudinal bands (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F30323CBFB97FE6E" box="[1056,1104,489,511]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1157,1179]" captionTargetBox="[369,1027,170,1103]" captionTargetId="figure-177@2.[359,1040,164,1126]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 4–11. C. difficilis. 4 — ♀, habitus, left; 5 — mesonotum, dorsally; 6 — wing (SIZK); 7 — abdomen; 8 — epandrium; 9 — glans; 10 — aculeus, ventrally; 11 — same, apex, enlarged (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452428/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 5</figureCitation>
); oviscape as long as 3 aculeus 6 times as long as wide and with one pair of distinct steps at apex. ………...... 
<taxonomicName id="E1EB4D18FF8AFFA7F3472025FB0EFD8A" baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[1124,1225,518,540]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Campiglossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis id="149FEA89FF8AFFA7F3472025FB0EFD8A" box="[1124,1225,518,540]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">C. difficilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F7852001FB0EFDA8" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" box="[166,1225,547,569]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F7852001FB0EFDA8" box="[166,1225,547,569]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
— Wing pattern pale brown (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F6D22001FDE8FDA8" box="[497,559,547,569]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1731,1753]" captionTargetBox="[327,963,794,1710]" captionTargetId="figure-202@7.[327,964,779,1710]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 35–36. Campiglossa sp. 35 — ♀, habitus, right; 36 — wing (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452438/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 36</figureCitation>
); mesonotum without brownish longitudinal bands. 
<taxonomicName id="E1EB4D18FF8AFFA7F30D2001FB0EFDA8" box="[1070,1225,547,569]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Campiglossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undefined-5">Campiglossa sp.</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="9D1F2E3EFF8AFFA7F7852062FB0EFD3D" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F7852062FB0EFD1E" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F7852062FB0EFD1E" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
5 Stigma with two hyaline spots; apical hyaline spot of triangle small (triangle of large hyaline spots in the wing medial part: 3 at front margin, 
<quantity id="E1139B7EFF8AFFA7F554207FFD5AFDE2" box="[631,669,605,627]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
r2+3 cell and apical, at base of r4+5 cell) (
<figureCitation id="BED02A1EFF8AFFA7F316207FFBB3FDE2" box="[1077,1140,605,627]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1088,1110]" captionTargetBox="[344,1061,176,1053]" captionTargetId="figure-208@3.[320,1093,125,1082]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 12–16. C. grandinata. 12 — ♀, habitus, right; 13 — mesonotum, dorsally (SIZK); 14 — wing; 15 — glans; 16 — epandrium (SMNC)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6452430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6452430/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">fig. 14</figureCitation>
); base of mesonotal setae with brownish spots. ....................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="E1EB4D18FF8AFFA7F3672058FB0EFD1E" baseAuthorityName="Rondani" baseAuthorityYear="1870" box="[1092,1225,634,655]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Campiglossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandinata">
<emphasis id="149FEA89FF8AFFA7F3672058FB0EFD1E" box="[1092,1225,634,655]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">C. grandinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F78520B4FB0EFD3D" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" box="[166,1225,662,684]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F78520B4FB0EFD3D" box="[166,1225,662,684]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
— Stigma with one hyaline spot; Apical hyaline spot in triangle large (except male of 
<taxonomicName id="E1EB4D18FF8AFFA7F32520B4FBAEFD3D" baseAuthorityName="Loew" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1030,1129,662,684]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Campiglossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="misella">C. misella</taxonomicName>
). ........... 6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="9D1F2E3EFF8AFFA7F7852091FB0EFC8E" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<paragraph id="2654369BFF8AFFA7F7852091FB0EFD74" blockId="8.[166,1225,230,799]" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
<keyLead id="9D1A95AEFF8AFFA7F7852091FB0EFD74" pageId="8" pageNumber="259">
